<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <title>Lists</title>
    <body>
      <p> There are three types of lists:</p>
      <p>definition lists</p>
        <ul>which show terms and definitions</ul>
      <p> unordered lists</p>
        <ul> which show bullets</ul>
      <p>ordered lists</p>
        <ul> which show numbers or letters</ul>

    <p>Unordered lists can have a type attribute which can be applied to the UL or the LI tag. The three values allowed are:</p>

   <ul style = "list-style-type:square"> <li>list type =  "square"</li></ul>
   <ul style = "list-style-type:disc"> <li>list type =  "disc"</li></ul>
   <ul style = "list-style-type:circle"> <li>list type =  "circle"</li></ul>
</p>
<p>
  Ordered lists can have a type attribute too. Used along with a start attribute they can show:
    <ol type="a"> <li>lower case letters</li></ol>
    <ol type="A" start = "2"> <li>upper case letters</li></ol>
    <ol type="i" start = "3"> <li>lower case roman numerals</li></ol>
    <ol type="I" start = "4"> <li>upper case roman numerals</li></ol>
    <ol type="1" start = "5"> <li>numbers</li></ol>
</p>

</body>


    
	
      
      
   
